SECOND REGULAR SESSION
[PERFECTED]
HOUSE COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE FOR
HOUSE BILL NO. 3175
103RD GENERAL ASSEMBLY
6579H.04P JOSEPH ENGLER, Chief Clerk
AN ACT
To amend chapter 301, RSMo, by adding thereto one new section relating to persons with
impaired or limited ability to communicate with law enforcement.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the state of Missouri, as follows:
Section A. Chapter 301, RSMo, is amended by adding thereto one new section, to be
2 known as section 301.287, to read as follows:
301.287. 1. This section shall be known and referred to as "Mason's Law".
2 2. Beginning January 1, 2027, a resident of this state with a health condition or
3 disability that limits or impairs the ability to effectively communicate with law
4 enforcement may, at any time, apply to the department of revenue for a designation that
5 shall be associated with the person's driver's license issued under chapter 302 and motor
6 vehicle license plate or plates issued under this chapter and available to law enforcement
7 under the Missouri uniform law enforcement system (MULES) established under
8 chapter 43.
9 3. The initial application, which shall be on a form prescribed by the department
10 and made available on the department's website, shall by signed by a physician licensed
11 under chapter 334, or a psychologist licensed under chapter 337, certifying that:
12 (1) The applicant or the applicant's child, parent, or spouse has a physical or
13 mental health condition that is likely to impair the ability to effectively communicate
14 with law enforcement; and
15 (2) The physician or psychologist has determined that the applicant or the
16 applicant's child, parent, or spouse will have the communication impairment for at least
17 five years.
EXPLANATION — Matter enclosed in bold-faced brackets [thus] in the above bill is not enacted and is
intended to be omitted from the law. Matter in bold-face type in the above bill is proposed language.

HCS HB 3175 2
18 4. Upon submission of an application and approval by the department, the
19 department shall prepare an entry in the department's records that is accessible to law
20 enforcement via MULES and that indicates that the applicant or the applicant's child,
21 parent, or spouse has a physical or mental health condition that may impair the ability
22 to effectively communicate with law enforcement. Such entry as related to the
23 applicant’s driver’s license shall remain active until the expiration of their driver’s
24 license. Such entry as related to the applicant’s motor vehicle license plate or plates
25 shall remain active for a period of five years, unless the applicant requests that such
26 designation be removed from the records. Upon expiration of the five-year period, the
27 designation in MULES may be reactivated upon the filing of a renewal form with the
28 department signed by a physician licensed under chapter 334, or a psychologist licensed
29 under chapter 337, certifying that:
30 (1) The applicant or the applicant's child, parent, or spouse has a physical or
31 mental health condition that is likely to impair the ability to effectively communicate
32 with law enforcement; and
33 (2) The physician or psychologist has determined that the applicant or the
34 applicant's child, parent, or spouse will have the communication impairment for at least
35 five years.
36 5. The department of public safety shall issue guidance and education materials
37 to all law enforcement agencies in this state to promote awareness of the designation
38 established under this section.
39 6. The department of revenue may promulgate all necessary rules and
40 regulations for the administration of this section. Any rule or portion of a rule, as that
41 term is defined in section 536.010, that is created under the authority delegated in this
42 section shall become effective only if it complies with and is subject to all of the
43 provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable, section 536.028. This section and chapter
44 536 are nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with the general assembly
45 pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay the effective date, or to disapprove and annul
46 a rule are subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of rulemaking authority
47 and any rule proposed or adopted after August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
